05067nam a22007935i 9780231851244DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017051003  a97802318512447 a10.7312/ston179202doi  a(DE-B1597)499039  a(OCoLC)1054878061  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPN1998.3.L544bS76 2018 4aPN1998.3.L544 7aPER0040102bisacsh04a791.4302/330921 aStone, Rob, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cinema of Richard Linklater :bWalk, Don't Run /cRob Stone. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b32 film stills or images provided by Linklater or IPC.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDirectors' Cuts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Walk, Don’t Run: The Cinema of Richard Linklater -- t2. Locating Linklater -- t3. Crafting Contradictions -- t4. The Form and Content of Slack -- t5. Walking and Talking -- t6. Dreamstate, USA: The Metaphysics of Animation -- t7. Winging It -- t8. The Spaces In Between -- tFilmography -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Slacker (1991), a foundational work of independent American cinema, to the Before trilogy, Richard Linklater’s critically acclaimed films and aesthetic ambition have earned him a place as one of the most important contemporary directors. In this second edition of The Cinema of Richard Linklater, Rob Stone shows how Linklater’s latest films have redefined our understanding of his work. He offers critical discussions and analysis of all of Linklater’s films, including Before Midnight (2013) and Everybody Wants Some!! (2016), as well as new interviews with Linklater and a chapter on Boyhood (2014), hailed as one of the best films of the twenty-first century.Stone explores the theoretical, practical, contextual, and metaphysical elements in Linklater’s filmography, especially his experimentation with cinematic representations of time and growth. He demonstrates that fanciful lives and lucid dreams are as central as alternative notions of America and time to Linklater’s films. Stone also considers Linklater’s collaborative working practices, his deployment of such techniques as rotoscoping, and his innovative distribution strategies. Thoroughly revised, updated, and extended, the book includes analysis of all of Linklater’s films, including Dazed and Confused (1993), Waking Life (2011), and A Scanner Darkly (2006) as well as his documentaries, short films, and side projects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aLinklater, Richardd1960-xCriticism and interpretation. 0aLinklater, Richard,d1960-xCriticism and interpretation. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / Direction & Production.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060660708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2018z9783110603088oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2018 Englishz978311060397208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/ston1792040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231851244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231851244/original  a978-3-11-060397-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060425-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060660-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-P